replies.bodyText:
I think the use case is very small, but it's conceivable that user code relies on the return value being the previous value (they get values out of it expecting old values). So something like this could be more correct if I'm not mistaken.
Context current = Context.current();
current.scope = this.context.makeCurrent();
return current;

@nilebox yep, added
@anuraaga Did you mean something like this?
    // Get the current context, soon to be replaced
    Context prev = Context.current();
    // Replace the scope with the scope of `this` context
    scope = context.makeCurrent();
    // Return the previous context and the current scope
    context = prev;
    return this;

This would make the context inconsistent, as it would replace this context with the previous context every time attach() is called, whereas before attach() is called the context would be this context.

